# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: odata-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] In computing, **content negotiation** refers to mechanisms defined as a part of HTTP that make it possible to serve different versions of a document (or more generally, representations of a resource) at the same URI, so that user agents can specify which version fits their capabilities the best.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] One classical use of this mechanism is to serve an image in GIF or PNG format, so that a browser that cannot display PNG images (e.g.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] MS Internet Explorer 4) will be served the GIF version.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] A resource may be available in several different representations; for example, it might be available in different languages or different media types.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] One way of selecting the most appropriate choice is to give the user an index page and let them select the most appropriate choice; however it is often possible to automate the choice based on some selection criteria.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] HTTP provides for several different content negotiation mechanisms including: server-driven (or proactive), agent-driven (or reactive), transparent, and/or hybrid combinations thereof.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] Server-driven or proactive content negotiation is performed by algorithms on the server which choose among the possible variant representations.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] This is commonly performed based on user agent-provided acceptance criteria.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] To summarize how this works, when a user agent submits a request to a server, the user agent informs the server what media types or other aspects of content presentation it understands with ratings of how well it understands them.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] More precisely, the user agent provides HTTP headers that lists acceptable aspects of the resource and quality factors for them.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] The server is then able to supply the version of the resource that best fits the user agent's needs.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] Where the 'q' - quality - factor for German is higher than that for English.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] Multiple HTTP headers are often supplied together for content format or, specifically media type, language and a few other aspects of a resource.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] In addition to the commonly used `Accept` header for Media Type, the `Accept-Language` header for language negotiation, RFC 7231 also describes `Accept-Charset` & `Accept-Encodings` for character encodings and content codings (compression) respectively.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] Neither RFC 7231 nor the more recent related specifications such as *Content Negotiation by Profile* specify how to resolve trade-offs in cases where different headers specify conflicting requirements, such as, in the above example, choosing between an HTML page in English and a GIF image in German.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] Agent-driven or reactive content negotiation is performed by algorithms in the user-agent which choose among the possible variant representations.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] This is commonly performed based on a server provided list of representations and metadata about them.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] To summarize how this works, when a user agent submits a request to a server, the server informs the user-agent which representations it has available as well as any metadata it has about each representation (e.g., content-type, quality, language, etc.).
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] The user-agent then resubmits the request to a specific URL for the chosen representation.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] This can be automatically chosen by the user-agent or the user-agent can present the user with the choices and the user can directly choose such.
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] More precisely, the server responds with either 300 Multiple Choices or 406 Not Acceptable (when server-driven, user-agent acceptance criteria are provided but the server cannot automatically make a selection).
[src:odata-protocol/content-negotiation] Unfortunately HTTP leaves the format of the list of representations and metadata along with selection mechanisms unspecified.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] In computing, **Open Data Protocol** (**OData**) is an open protocol that allows the creation and consumption of queryable and interoperable Web service APIs in a standard way.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] Versions 1.0, 2.0, and 3.0 are released under the Microsoft Open Specification Promise.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] Version 4.0 was standardized at OASIS, with a release in March 2014.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] In April 2015 OASIS submitted OData v4 and OData JSON Format v4 to ISO/IEC JTC 1 for approval as an international standard.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] The protocol enables the creation and consumption of HTTP-based Web APIs, which allow Web clients to publish and edit resources, identified using URLs and defined in a data model, using simple HTTP messages.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] OData shares some similarities with JDBC and with ODBC; like ODBC, OData is not limited to relational databases.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] After initial development by Microsoft, OData became a standardized protocol of the OASIS OData Technical Committee (TC).
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] TC participants include CA Technologies, Citrix Systems, IBM, Microsoft, Progress Software, Red Hat, SAP SE and SDL.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] OData is a protocol for the creation and consumption of Web APIs.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] OData thus builds on HTTP, AtomPub, and JSON using URIs to address and access data feed resources.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] The service document lists entity sets, functions, and singletons that can be retrieved.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] Clients can use the service document to navigate the model in a hypermedia-driven fashion.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] The metadata document describes the types, sets, functions and actions understood by the OData service.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] Clients can use the metadata document to understand how to query and interact with entities in the service.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] The metadata document is available at *http://host/service/$metadata*.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] OData uses the HTTP verbs to indicate the operations on the resources.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] URLs requested from an OData endpoint may include query options.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] The OData protocol specifies various 'system query options' endpoints should accept, these can be used to filter, order, map or paginate data.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] Query options can be appended to a URL after a `?` character and are separated by `&` characters; each option consists of a `$`-sign prefixed name and its value, separated by a `=` sign, for example: `OData/Products?$top=2&$orderby=Name`.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] A number of logical operators and functions are defined for use when filtering data, for example: `OData/Products?$filter=Price lt 10.00 and startswith(Name,'M')` requests products with a price smaller than 10 and a name starting with the letter 'M'.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] OData uses different formats for representing data and the data model.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] In OData protocol version 4.0, JSON format is the standard for representing data, with the Atom format still being in committee specification stage.
[src:odata-protocol/open-data-protocol] For representing the data model, the Common Schema Definition Language (CSDL) is used, which defines an XML representation of the entity data model exposed by OData services.
[src:odata-protocol/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:odata-protocol/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:odata-protocol/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:odata-protocol/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:odata-protocol/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:odata-protocol/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:odata-protocol/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] In a web service, a web technology such as HTTP is used for transferring machine-readable file formats such as XML and JSON.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] In practice, a web service commonly provides an object-oriented web-based interface to a database server, utilized for example by another web server, or by a mobile app, that provides a user interface to the end-user.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Many organizations that provide data in formatted HTML pages will also provide that data on their server as XML or JSON, often through a Web service to allow syndication.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Another application offered to the end-user may be a mashup, where a Web server consumes several Web services at different machines and compiles the content into one user interface.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) is a dominant technology for Web services.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Developing from the combination of HTTP servers, JavaScript clients and Plain Old XML (as distinct from SOAP and W3C Web Services), now it is frequently used with JSON as well as, or instead of, XML.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Representational State Transfer (REST) is an architecture for well-behaved Web services that can function at Internet scale.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] A Web API is a development in Web services where emphasis has been moving to simpler representational state transfer (REST) based communications.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Restful APIs do not require XML-based Web service protocols (SOAP and WSDL) to support their interfaces.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] W3C Web Services may use SOAP over HTTP protocol, allowing less costly (more efficient) interactions over the Internet than via proprietary solutions like EDI/B2B.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Besides SOAP over HTTP, Web services can also be implemented on other reliable transport mechanisms like FTP.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] The term "Web service" describes a standardized way of integrating Web-based applications using the XML, SOAP, WSDL and UDDI open standards over an Internet Protocol backbone.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] XML is the data format used to contain the data and provide metadata around it, SOAP is used to transfer the data, WSDL is used for describing the services available and UDDI lists what services are available.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] A Web service is a method of communication between two electronic devices over a network.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] It is a software function provided at a network address over the Web with the service *always-on* as in the concept of utility computing.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Many organizations use multiple software systems for management.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Different software systems often need to exchange data with each other, and a Web service is a method of communication that allows two software systems to exchange this data over the Internet.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] The software system that requests data is called a *service requester*, whereas the software system that would process the request and provide the data is called a *service provider*.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Different software may use different programming languages, and hence there is a need for a method of data exchange that doesn't depend upon a particular programming language.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Most types of software can, however, interpret XML tags.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Thus, Web services can use XML files for data exchange.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] All of these rules for communication are defined in a file called WSDL (Web Services Description Language), which has a `.wsdl` extension.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] A directory called UDDI (Universal Description, Discovery, and Integration) defines which software system should be contacted for which type of data.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] So when one software system needs one particular report/data, it would go to the UDDI and find out which other systems it can contact for receiving that data.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Once the software system finds out which other systems it should contact, it would then contact that system using a special protocol called SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol).
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] The service provider system would first validate the data request by referring to the WSDL file, and then process the request and send the data under the SOAP protocol.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Automated tools can aid in the creation of a Web service.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] For services using WSDL, it is possible to either automatically generate WSDL for existing classes (a bottom-up model) or to generate a class skeleton given existing WSDL (a top-down model).
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Critics of non-RESTful Web services often complain that they are too complex and based upon large software vendors or integrators, rather than typical open source implementations.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] There are also concerns about performance due to Web services' use of XML as a message format and SOAP/HTTP in enveloping and transporting.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Functional and non-functional testing of Web services is done with the help of WSDL parsing.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Regression testing is performed by identifying the changes made to upgrade software.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Web service regression testing needs can be categorized in three different ways, namely, changes in WSDL, changes in the code, and selective re-testing of operations.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] We can capture the above three needs in three intermediate forms of Subset WSDL, namely, Difference WSDL (DWSDL), Unit WSDL (UWSDL), and Reduced WSDL (RWSDL), respectively.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] These three Subset WSDLs are then combined to form Combined WSDL (CWSDL) that is further used for regression testing of the Web service.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] This will help in Automated Web Service Change Management (AWSCM), by performing the selection of the relevant test cases to construct a reduced test suite from the old test suite.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Web services testing can also be automated using several test automation tools like SoapUI, Oracle Application Testing Suite (OATS), Unified Functional Testing, Selenium, etc.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Work-related to the capture and visualization of changes made to a Web service.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] Visualization and computation of changes can be done in the form of intermediate artifacts (Subset WSDL).
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] The insight on the computation of change impact is helpful in testing, top-down development and reduce regression testing.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] AWSCM is a tool that can identify subset operations in a WSDL file to construct a subset WSDL.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] While UDDI was intended to serve as a service directory and become the means to discovering web services, many vendors discontinued their UDDI solutions or repositories between 2005 and 2008, including Microsoft, SAP, IBM, among others.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] A key study published in WWW2008 Conference (Beijing, China) presented the state of SOAP-based web services and concluded that only 63% of the available SOAP-based web services at the time of the study were actually active or can be invoked.
[src:odata-protocol/web-service] The study also found that search engines were becoming an ideal source for searching for web services compared to that of service registries like the UDDI due its design complexity.
